title: Bernard Shaw and XIX century tradition (Art Literature).pdf
description:
University of Oklahoma Press | 1958 | Pdf | Eng | 222 pg | 36 MB

GEORGE BERNARD SHAW, whose true likeness was splendidly revealed in the photograph by Karsch, Ottawa, is "one of the few contemporary writers whose position in world literature is almost universally believed to be secure," says Julian B. Kaye at the beginning of this book. A few sentences later, however, Kaye notes ironically that Shaw, a man of profound understanding and personal shrewdness, "gave, for the last thirty-five years of his life, the wrong answers to almost all the questions that have perplexed our age."
